- displacement
environmental_stressor: Acoustic pollution from increased commercial shipping and
  dam construction drowning out natural river sounds essential for traditional fishing
  methods
family_situation: Widow, her three children moved to Wuhan for factory work. Granddaughter
  visits monthly, trying to learn the old songs but struggles with the Mandarin-dominated
  education system erasing their local dialect.
file_name: last_human.json
final_thought: The river no longer speaks in the old language - only the roar of progress
  drowning out twenty generations of wisdom.
last_days_scenario: "Chen sits by the Yangtze at dawn, holding her grandfather's carved\
  \ bamboo pole. The water churns brown with sediment from the new dam upstream. Container\
  \ ships blast their horns every few minutes, their engines drowning out the subtle\
  \ sounds she once used to locate fish schools. Her nets come up empty - the fish\
  \ have fled or died, and she can no longer hear their movements through the industrial\
  \ cacophony. \n\nThe government relocation notice crumples in her pocket. Her traditional\
  \ fishing grounds will become a new port facility next month. At 67, she's too old\
  \ to learn new skills, too poor to relocate to approved areas. Her granddaughter\
  \ texts in simplified characters Chen barely recognizes, asking if she's \"ready\
  \ to modernize.\" \n\nChen whispers the old river songs - prayers that once called\
  \ fish and predicted floods - but her voice is lost in the diesel rumble of progress.\
  \ Like the baiji dolphins her grandmother once described as \"river goddesses,\"\
  \ Chen and her ancient knowledge are being erased by the same forces: habitat destruction\
  \ disguised as development, acoustic pollution severing communication with the natural\
  \ world, and the systematic elimination of indigenous wisdom in favor of industrial\
  \ efficiency.\n\nThe bamboo pole, carved with symbols her great-grandmother could\
  \ read in the water's surface, now points toward a river that no longer remembers\
  \ its own name."
